    "questions": [
        {
            "id": "e1eb1aba8feb4fe4ac5f0",
            "questionText": "A tuning fork with a frequency of $!$440~\\mathrm{Hz}$!$ is used to create resonance in a pipe that is open at one end and closed at the other. The speed of sound in air is $!$343~\\mathrm{m/s}$!$. Determine the wavelength corresponding to the fifth harmonic in this closed pipe configuration.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "533a9c7979ab49d08bac7",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by recalling the nature of standing waves in a closed pipe. In this configuration, only certain harmonics can form a resonance. Which statement best describes the allowed harmonics for a pipe that is open at one end and closed at the other?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0deb0cf3-4f02-472f-9b66-a770ccf171bc"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "Only odd harmonics occur",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Only even harmonics occur",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Both odd and even harmonics occur",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "bb2b9a507fc04c10bdbfc",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have considered the harmonic conditions, let\u2019s identify the relationship that links the frequency ($!$f$!$), the speed of sound ($!$v$!$), and the wavelength ($!$\\lambda$!$) of a wave. Which of the following formulas correctly represents this relation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "524f0548-0ea5-4a4b-8776-652b87aa3602"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f=\\frac{v}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f=\\frac{\\lambda}{v}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f=v\\cdot\\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "168f5574c0754a89be6d0",
                    "stepText": "Using the equation you identified, rearrange it to express the wavelength ($!$\\lambda$!$) in terms of the speed ($!$v$!$) and the frequency ($!$f$!$). Which of the following expressions correctly isolates $!$\\lambda$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "524f0548-0ea5-4a4b-8776-652b87aa3602"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda=\\frac{v}{f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda=v\\cdot f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda=\\frac{f}{v}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "7568ff184952436699e09",
                    "stepText": "Now, substitute the provided values ($!$v=343~\\mathrm{m/s}$!$ and $!$f=440~\\mathrm{Hz}$!$) into the expression you obtained to calculate the wavelength corresponding to the fifth harmonic. What is the numerical value of the wavelength? (Round your answer appropriately.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.78"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "524f0548-0ea5-4a4b-8776-652b87aa3602",
                        "0deb0cf3-4f02-472f-9b66-a770ccf171bc"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "5eeed2e71b9b49938650c",
            "questionText": "A mass-spring system is set into vertical oscillation with damping. After the mass is released, its amplitude decreases to $!$\\frac{1}{e}$!$ of its initial amplitude after 5 complete cycles. Given that the initial (undamped) frequency is $!$2.0\\,Hz$!$, what is the approximate frequency of the damped oscillation?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "44cdc95ee75141fa8b610",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by finding the period $!$T$!$ of the undamped oscillation using the relationship between period and frequency. Identify the correct formula to compute $!$T$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{1}{f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = f^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f65a2fd4174c4931bc152",
                    "stepText": "Given that the amplitude falls to $!$\\frac{1}{e}$!$ of its initial value after 5 cycles, we need to relate the damping constant $!$\\delta$!$ and the period $!$T$!$. Identify the correct expression that relates $!$\\delta$!$ to $!$T$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "77fc2045-58a6-40d8-8660-0b520dd6d8b8"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\delta = \\frac{1}{5T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\delta = \\frac{1}{T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\delta = 5T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "bc08b869b5794f6a8cd25",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the expression from the previous step and the period found in Step 1, calculate the damping constant $!$\\delta$!$. (Recall that the period $!$T$!$ is the reciprocal of the frequency.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.4"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s^{-1}",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "77fc2045-58a6-40d8-8660-0b520dd6d8b8"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "c116691c810e4bca9a02e",
                    "stepText": "Next, determine the undamped angular frequency $!$\\omega_0$!$ using the relationship between angular frequency and the oscillation frequency. Identify the correct formula for $!$\\omega_0$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_0 = 2\\pi f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_0 = \\frac{f}{2\\pi}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_0 = \\sqrt{2\\pi f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d67d0a0ad26f42a2b5529",
                    "stepText": "Using the undamped frequency $!$f_0 = 2.0\\,Hz$!$, calculate the undamped angular frequency $!$\\omega_0$!$ in radians per second.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "12.57"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "280ff4a1825d4e99b9251",
                    "stepText": "For a lightly damped system, the damped angular frequency is given by an expression that takes into account both the undamped angular frequency and the damping constant. Identify the correct formula for computing the damped angular frequency $!$\\omega_d$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_d = \\sqrt{\\omega_0^2 - \\delta^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_d = \\omega_0 - \\delta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega_d = \\omega_0\\delta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "b1b4dbbf38bf4a4fb5696",
                    "stepText": "Finally, compute the damped oscillation frequency $!$f_d$!$. First, determine $!$\\omega_d$!$ using the formula from Step 6 and then convert it back to frequency using the relation $!$f_d = \\frac{\\omega_d}{2\\pi}$!$. What is the approximate value of $!$f_d$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.0"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "Hz",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
